Durban - Fifteen school children were injured after the minibus taxi they were travelling in crashed into a traffic light on Booth Road in Cato Manor, near the Durban city, on Tuesday morning. Garrith Jamieson, Rescue Care Operations Director said, “Rescue Care Paramedics arrived on the scene to find the taxi on top of the robot. Multiple school children on there way to school were injured and immediately more ambulances were dispatched to the scene. A total of fifteen school children had sustained minor injuries and were stabilised on the scene before being transported to various Durban hospitals for the further care that they required”. He said the events that led to the crash were unknown but police were on the scene investigating. In another incident, nine people including school children were injured in a three car pile-up in Montclair, south of Durban. "Rescue Care Paramedics arrived on the scene to find the vehicles had collided in a rear end format. A total of nine people from the three vehicles including children had sustained various injuries. More ambulances were dispatched to assist with the multiple casualty scene," he said. Police could not be reached at the time of publication. On Monday, six people, including school children were left injured when the vehicle they were travelling in was involved crashed into two other vehicles. The vehicle the children were travelling in was transporting them to school in the morning when the incident took place. Daily News